    Closes GH-229

Overrides doesn't match relative paths

JSHint doesn't override configuration when it is called with a
relative path, like `./src/bar.js` when the configuration is:

```json
{
  overrides: {
    "src/bar.js"
  }
}
```

Only apply forin check to forin loops.

This change corrects the behaviour of JSHints forin option
on forof loops; the two share many checks, but this:

    for (var x of [1, 2, 3]) {
        // 
    }

should not result in the warning reported by jshint/jshint#1079:

> The body of a for in should be wrapped in an if statement to filter
> unwanted properties from the prototype.

Support Object Short Notation

This adds support for object short notation:

```javascript
function f(x, y) { return {x: x, y: y}; }
// Object Short Notation
function f(x, y) { return {x, y}; }
```

Support for this feature is limited to `esnext` mode.

Do not assume JSON block when mapping array

If the following code snippet is the first line of a program, JSHint
incorrectly assumes it is JSON when doing array destructuring checks:

```
['foo', 'bar', 'baz'].forEach(function(name) {
  console.log(name);
});
```

Fixes #1446

Strip comments in JSON by parsing instead of regex

Using regex for this is just too fragile.

I've changed it out to use the strip-json-comments module instead: https://github.com/sindresorhus/strip-json-comments

Example of where the existing one will fail:

    console.log(removeComments('{"a":"b//c"}'));
    //=> {"a":"b

Fix read of property "use strict" of undefined.

Fixes jshint crash with:

```js
// jshint esnext: true, globalstrict: true
"use strict";
var a = () => 42;
```

Always do the 'unstack', and after the last 'advance', for good measure.

This fixes the case where:

```js
// jshint esnext: true, unused: true
[a,b] = [1,2];
let c = 42;
```

Accept "class C extends AssignmentExpression {}".

Examples:

class C extends func() {}
class C extends arr[0] {}
class C extends "str" {}

Add support for +W### option in comments to unignore an warning

Allows a warning to be ignored for a number of lines, and then
unignored after. For example:

    var y = Object.create(null);
    // ...

    //jshint -W089
    for (var x in y) {
        // ...
    }
    //jshint +W089

suppresses the warning about not wrapping a "for in" in an if in this
case, but leaves the warning enabled for later occurrences in the
file.

